You’re touching on two related ideas: neural wiring through use and how constant divided attention affects the brain. Let’s separate them.

1. Connections create dendrites

In a broad sense, you’re right about the mechanism. The brain strengthens connections when circuits fire together.

This principle is often summarized as Hebbian Learning.

repeated activation
→ synapses strengthen
→ dendritic branching increases
→ pathway becomes easier to use

That’s how skills, habits, and knowledge form. Practice literally reshapes neural connections.

So every time you repeat a pattern of attention or thought, you’re reinforcing a pathway.

⸻

2. Phone + TV + multitasking

There is research suggesting heavy media multitasking can affect attention systems.

The issue isn’t really a literal split brain (that term usually refers to a rare surgical condition involving the corpus callosum). Instead it’s more like:

multiple stimuli
→ rapid attention switching
→ shallow processing

The brain is not truly doing two complex things simultaneously. What usually happens is:

task A
↓
switch
↓
task B
↓
switch back

Those switches cost cognitive energy and reduce depth of processing.

Some studies show that people who constantly multitask with media may:
	•	have more difficulty filtering distractions
	•	show reduced sustained attention
	•	retain less information from each stream

⸻

3. Why it can feel like “partial knowledge”

When attention is split across many inputs:

information intake ↑
but
depth of processing ↓

So people may recognize lots of fragments but struggle to recall details or execute complex tasks quickly.

That can give the feeling of:

familiarity without mastery


⸻

4. The brain can still recover

The important part is that the brain is plastic.

If someone shifts toward:
	•	focused reading
	•	deep work
	•	skill practice
	•	quieter environments

the relevant circuits strengthen again.

Neural pathways adapt to how attention is used most often.

⸻

5. Your earlier gradient idea actually fits here

Attention acts like a learning gradient.

attention
→ neural reinforcement
→ stronger pathways

Whatever repeatedly captures attention tends to shape the brain’s wiring.

⸻

If you’re interested, there’s an even deeper angle to your observation: modern media environments may be training the brain to operate in a different cognitive mode than humans evolved for. The difference between deep-focus cognition and rapid-scanning cognition is becoming a major topic in neuroscience and psychology.